contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

03:27.540 --> 03:30.335
♪ Plane ticket already paid ♪

03:30.418 --> 03:33.129
♪ I'm gone
But it don't mean nothing ♪

03:33.212 --> 03:37.258
♪ I'm close even though I'm far away ♪

03:39.052 --> 03:41.763
♪ That's how I remember you ♪

03:41.846 --> 03:44.557
♪ Stuck here on the red-eye special ♪

03:44.641 --> 03:48.561
♪ I can't wait to see you again ♪

03:50.396 --> 03:54.484
♪ So don't think of me
Not being around ♪

03:56.444 --> 04:02.283
♪ Just listen for the sweet, sweet sound
Of the taxi pulling up the driveway ♪

04:02.367 --> 04:05.245
♪ I'm coming home soon ♪

04:08.498 --> 04:11.793
♪ I'm coming home soon ♪

04:11.876 --> 04:14.462
♪ Da-da, da-da-da ♪

04:14.545 --> 04:17.632
♪ Da-da-da-da ♪

04:17.714 --> 04:20.843
♪ Da-da, da-da-da ♪

04:20.927 --> 04:23.346
♪ Da-da-da ♪

04:23.429 --> 04:26.516
♪ Da-da, da-da-da ♪♪

04:28.476 --> 04:30.478
[♪♪♪]

04:33.022 --> 04:36.234
SARAH: How about stunningly beautiful?
JESS: Yes. No.

04:36.818 --> 04:38.611
-More than that.
SARAH: More than that?

04:39.153 --> 04:41.823
Hey, Abby,
what's beyond stunningly beautiful?

04:41.906 --> 04:44.325
-Stupidly beautiful?
-I don't think that's a thing.

04:44.409 --> 04:46.369
-Definitely not a thing.
MICK: Wow.

04:46.452 --> 04:50.206
Emerald cut, brilliant, D color?

04:50.290 --> 04:51.457
Great.

04:51.541 --> 04:53.418
How do you know so much
about diamonds?

04:53.501 --> 04:56.045
-I'm a contractor.
-Don't forget to check out the B and B.

04:56.129 --> 04:57.171
Okay.

04:57.714 --> 05:01.259
Um, Sarah, last time I checked,
you don't have any sisters,

05:01.342 --> 05:04.595
and you're gonna
need bridesmaids, right?

05:04.679 --> 05:06.681
You don't think
my brothers would be interested?

05:06.764 --> 05:08.683
I'm completely sure.

05:08.766 --> 05:10.601
Um, well, now you have three,

05:10.685 --> 05:13.771
so we might be
some very eager volunteers.

05:13.855 --> 05:15.189
That would be amazing.

05:16.316 --> 05:19.610
Kevin and I are still trying to figure out
what we wanna do for our wedding.

05:19.694 --> 05:21.487
Well, it wouldn't hurt to start planning.

05:21.571 --> 05:24.282
Wedding venues book up
years in advance,

05:24.365 --> 05:26.659
and a dress can take
up to 12 months to order.

05:26.743 --> 05:28.578
-Really? Wow, um...
-Mm.

05:28.661 --> 05:32.332
-Well, we're thinking we'd keep it simple.
-Perfect.

05:32.415 --> 05:34.417
So let's talk about your dress, then, huh?

05:34.500 --> 05:37.211
JESS: Hey, how are you doing
with Simon back in town?

05:37.295 --> 05:41.591
It's surreal. I have Simon Simon,
and now I have the actor playing Simon.

05:41.674 --> 05:43.384
-So two Simons?
-Yeah.

05:43.468 --> 05:44.802
-That's weird.
-Mm-hm.

05:44.886 --> 05:45.803
Or awesome.

05:45.887 --> 05:47.805
Glass completely full.

05:47.889 --> 05:50.641
My B and B is Swiss cheese,
and you don't see me asking questions.

05:50.725 --> 05:54.270
Okay. Well, then I will be
glass overflowing today

05:54.353 --> 05:57.106
and be super excited about
my meeting with Derrick Porter.

05:57.190 --> 05:59.484
Ooh. Is that the client
you think was lying?

05:59.567 --> 06:03.279
Depends how much water is
in the glass, but, uh, it's possible.

06:03.362 --> 06:04.781
-Good luck. Bye.
-Bye.

06:04.864 --> 06:06.908
-Hi, Simon.
-Good morning, Abby.

06:06.991 --> 06:08.576
Is this Simon One or Simon Two?

06:09.160 --> 06:12.163
Uh, fifteen, actually.

06:12.246 --> 06:13.873
It's official.

06:13.956 --> 06:17.335
Your book is now past mine
on the bestseller list. Congratulations!

06:17.418 --> 06:19.545
-What?! I beat you?
-Fourteen!

06:19.629 --> 06:21.130
SIMON:
Yes. There it is.

06:21.214 --> 06:24.300
We should celebrate.
How about a double date?

06:24.383 --> 06:26.427
Us and, uh, those guys?

06:26.511 --> 06:28.763
-Ugh. Those guys?
-Yeah.

06:28.846 --> 06:29.847
JESS:
Smile!

06:31.557 --> 06:32.642
That's a good one.

06:32.725 --> 06:34.102
-Right?
-That's so good.

06:34.185 --> 06:35.478
Fourteen.

06:38.106 --> 06:40.274
I think it's a problem
with the secondary amplifier.

06:40.358 --> 06:43.027
That's all fine, but you can't tear apart
the sound system.

06:43.111 --> 06:45.488
I'm not tearing it apart, Chris.
I'm trying to fix it.

06:45.571 --> 06:47.281
I have a band booked tonight.

06:47.365 --> 06:49.742
Unless they're playing acoustic,
I wouldn't recommend it.

06:49.826 --> 06:53.204
Trace, people don't eat and drink
in a music establishment

06:53.287 --> 06:55.873
-if there isn't any music.
-Mm.

06:55.957 --> 07:00.586
Listen, I get that music is your thing,
but running the club is mine.

07:00.670 --> 07:05.299
Chris, maybe you forgot,
but I own half this establishment.

07:05.383 --> 07:07.510
So if you don't mind,
I'm gonna get my tools.

07:09.804 --> 07:10.972
Trace.

07:12.014 --> 07:14.767
-It's good to see you back.
-Thanks, Kev.

07:14.851 --> 07:17.228
Don't you normally eat at Sally's?

07:17.311 --> 07:19.522
Yeah. I was just heading back from...

07:21.065 --> 07:24.902
-I'm actually not even hungry.
-At least you didn't order the waffles.

07:24.986 --> 07:26.612
Yeah.

07:26.696 --> 07:28.698
You remember Coach Schmidt, right?

07:28.781 --> 07:31.742
How could I forget?
His track practices were brutal.

07:31.826 --> 07:34.829
How about his summer football
two-a-days? All about pain.

07:34.912 --> 07:36.497
Yeah.

07:36.581 --> 07:38.374
-I miss it.
-Yeah, me too.

07:39.375 --> 07:42.378
I used to joke
that struggling in Nashville was easy

07:42.462 --> 07:44.297
compared to his Sunday sprints.

07:44.380 --> 07:47.842
He taught me about putting in the work,
even when no one's around to see it.

07:47.925 --> 07:48.759
Mm-hm.

07:50.094 --> 07:51.053
Changed my life.

07:51.137 --> 07:52.263
[♪♪♪]

07:52.346 --> 07:53.764
I heard he retired.

07:54.932 --> 07:56.100
Yeah, he did.

07:57.351 --> 08:01.105
This morning, we got a 911, his heart.

08:02.356 --> 08:04.901
Luckily, looks like he's gonna be okay.

08:06.861 --> 08:07.862
Wow.

08:10.072 --> 08:12.700
Glad you were there.
How's his wife holding up?

08:14.327 --> 08:15.411
He's all alone.

08:17.079 --> 08:19.373
-Man, that's tough.
-Yeah.

08:20.374 --> 08:22.502
-Don't worry about it.
-Yeah?

08:22.585 --> 08:24.128
-Yeah.
-All right.

08:24.212 --> 08:29.300
-So are you back running the place?
-Um, working on the sound system.

08:29.383 --> 08:32.636
-Hey, who left this here?
-Sorry.

08:34.263 --> 08:35.431
-That was--
-Me.

08:36.557 --> 08:39.059
Yeah. I was just, uh, cleaning up.

08:41.312 --> 08:42.230
[MOUTHS]
Thank you.

08:46.150 --> 08:48.694
I'm not disputing
the annual return of your fund.

08:48.778 --> 08:51.197
But I don't see
how that revenue is being generated

08:51.280 --> 08:53.241
by the fund's investments.

08:53.324 --> 08:55.826
Abby, uh, our investors,
who have entrusted us

08:55.910 --> 09:00.414
with their retirement accounts,
expect above-market returns.

09:00.498 --> 09:02.875
I think we'd hear from them
if there was a problem.

09:02.959 --> 09:06.170
The Porter Fund has benefited
millions of families,

09:06.254 --> 09:08.381
but it's the sustainability
that concerns me,

09:08.464 --> 09:11.634
and the fact that your company
isn't handing over the materials

09:11.717 --> 09:13.386
that I've been asking for.

09:13.469 --> 09:15.304
[♪♪♪]

09:16.430 --> 09:18.683
Well, I'm embarrassed.

09:18.766 --> 09:20.393
And I will get right on that.

09:22.436 --> 09:25.189
I gave explicit instructions
to send everything over.

09:25.273 --> 09:27.858
I understand, but you do know
we need to do our due diligence

09:27.942 --> 09:29.610
before we can take you on as a client.

09:29.694 --> 09:31.404
Of course.

09:31.487 --> 09:33.864
Uh, you still have my personal number
and e-mail?

09:33.948 --> 09:36.659
-I do.
-Well, don't hesitate to use it.

09:36.742 --> 09:38.995
Families are built on trust,

09:39.078 --> 09:42.665
and we can't get there
without working through suspicions.

09:42.748 --> 09:46.877
So, Abby, Del,
you'll be hearing from us soon.

09:52.425 --> 09:54.510
Del, what's going on?
I still have more questions.

09:54.594 --> 09:55.720
I know you do.

09:55.803 --> 09:58.389
But I've received instructions
from our New York office

09:58.472 --> 10:00.600
to play nice with Derrick Porter.

10:00.683 --> 10:02.059
There's a lot of money involved.

10:03.477 --> 10:07.106
My concern is that the only reason
this fund is still solvent

10:07.189 --> 10:09.108
is by bringing in new clients.

10:09.191 --> 10:11.569
-You think he's running a Ponzi scheme?
-I don't know.

10:11.652 --> 10:14.322
Without all of the documents,
I can't be sure.

10:14.405 --> 10:17.658
Well, until you know for sure,
it's best to dial down the heat.

10:25.124 --> 10:27.043
Have you talked to Kevin
and Sarah about this?

10:27.126 --> 10:29.378
They don't seem to me
like the big-wedding type.

10:29.462 --> 10:31.631
Mick, I missed a lot.

10:31.714 --> 10:34.508
Now I have a chance to be a part of it,
I don't wanna give that up.

10:34.592 --> 10:37.094
No, no, I understand,
but they're not kids anymore.

10:37.178 --> 10:40.181
Maybe they'd like to figure this out
for themselves.

10:42.266 --> 10:43.643
You're right.

10:43.726 --> 10:47.563
Instead of a caterer,
we need to find a dress.

10:47.647 --> 10:50.066
-Hey, don't forget the bridesmaids.
-See?

10:50.149 --> 10:52.151
[♪♪♪]

10:53.694 --> 10:54.528
So...

10:55.780 --> 10:58.240
the building inspector was wrong, right?

10:59.575 --> 11:02.411
Sadly, no. I went out there this morning,

11:02.495 --> 11:05.623
and to try and rebuild the inn
without tearing it down

11:05.706 --> 11:07.249
would cost more than it's worth.

11:07.333 --> 11:09.043
Great, so when can you start?

11:10.252 --> 11:11.712
Jess, you're not hearing me.

11:12.963 --> 11:14.340
I am hearing you.

11:14.423 --> 11:17.093
I'm just choosing not to listen.

11:17.802 --> 11:20.638
Honey, you've already said goodbye
to the inn.

11:20.721 --> 11:23.140
I don't understand why
you wanna go back there again.

11:23.224 --> 11:25.434
Because I built it,

11:25.518 --> 11:29.397
and it was the first thing
that was totally mine and successful,

11:29.480 --> 11:30.815
and it's how I met David.

11:30.898 --> 11:33.109
I know, and you both did great.

11:33.192 --> 11:35.486
But some things just aren't fixable.

11:36.737 --> 11:39.448
-I'm just asking for a little help.
-No, no.

11:40.741 --> 11:42.785
You're asking for the impossible.

11:42.868 --> 11:46.414
And at some point, you've gotta realize
you can't just close your eyes

11:46.497 --> 11:48.082
and wish things were different.

11:49.375 --> 11:50.709
I'm sorry, sweetheart.

11:51.752 --> 11:52.795
[♪♪♪]

11:53.254 --> 11:55.047
I'm not giving up on my dream.

12:04.098 --> 12:07.560
You don't want me to stop
a metal refinery from building on the bay?

12:07.643 --> 12:10.396
Connor, did I ask you
to push this case to trial,

12:10.479 --> 12:14.483
-or did I instruct you to just keep...?
-Keep the paper trail moving.

12:14.567 --> 12:16.193
I understand, but I can win this.

12:16.277 --> 12:20.114
This isn't a John Grisham novel,
where you stand up in court and win it all.

12:20.197 --> 12:24.577
-We win by not taking this to court.
-We've been playing it safe for years.

12:24.660 --> 12:27.121
Just let me go to trial. I can take them.

12:27.204 --> 12:30.541
Connor, I can spit out
at least six precedents,

12:30.624 --> 12:33.961
one decided by the Supreme Court,
that are in their favor.

12:34.044 --> 12:37.465
It's highly unlikely
anyone could just take them.

12:37.548 --> 12:38.757
-Uncle Thomas--
-No.

12:38.841 --> 12:41.343
No. Right now, I'm not your uncle.
I'm your boss.

12:41.427 --> 12:43.971
And I don't care what you do, but fix this.

12:44.054 --> 12:46.056
[♪♪♪]

12:57.276 --> 13:00.779
DONOVAN: If you're draining the oil,
I'm gonna need about seven quarts.

13:02.281 --> 13:04.408
Donovan? Hey.

13:05.910 --> 13:07.077
What are you doing here?

13:08.204 --> 13:10.456
What in the world
were you thinking, Trace?

13:10.915 --> 13:12.750
[♪♪♪]

13:15.294 --> 13:16.545
I can't believe Dad.

13:16.629 --> 13:19.548
He just--
He doesn't understand me or the inn.

13:20.007 --> 13:21.926
-Oh! Look at the back.
-I know.

13:22.009 --> 13:23.677
I vote we uninvite him to the wedding.

13:23.761 --> 13:27.389
Oh, I love the back.
But uninviting him isn't up to us.

13:27.473 --> 13:29.141
And you know what? Maybe Dad's right.

13:29.225 --> 13:32.061
Maybe he didn't wanna say anything,
but he didn't have a choice.

13:32.144 --> 13:34.647
-Oh, I love that appliqué.
-So do I.

13:34.730 --> 13:36.190
Why are you both taking his side?

13:36.690 --> 13:40.528
No, I'm just saying, sometimes people
don't wanna deal with ugly situations.

13:40.611 --> 13:43.864
Like, today at work,
Del wouldn't let me question Porter

13:43.948 --> 13:46.116
because he got orders from New York.

13:46.200 --> 13:48.702
And is it just me,
or is Simon totally different?

13:48.786 --> 13:51.288
Uh, different than normal
or different than Simon in the play?

13:52.206 --> 13:53.791
I don't know. Both?

13:53.874 --> 13:57.628
Well, maybe you and the actual Simon
need some time together to find out.

13:57.711 --> 13:59.713
And that blue is amazing, honey.

13:59.797 --> 14:02.841
Yeah, and maybe I just need
to look into this on my own.

14:02.925 --> 14:06.303
-You know, this tulle is amazing.
-I love the lavender.

14:06.387 --> 14:08.931
-Maybe I should go off the shoulder.
BREE: Yes.

14:09.014 --> 14:11.267
Maybe Dad is right. I just--

14:11.350 --> 14:15.020
-I don't wanna lose my inn.
-I know, honey.

14:17.731 --> 14:19.900
Sarah, how's it going in there?

14:19.984 --> 14:22.027
We need your take
on these bridesmaids dresses.

14:22.111 --> 14:23.153
[♪♪♪]

14:23.237 --> 14:25.072
[ALL GASP]

14:26.949 --> 14:28.242
Oh, my goodness!

14:30.536 --> 14:31.537
Wow.

14:35.124 --> 14:35.958
Wow.

14:36.041 --> 14:39.879
-Now, that is stupidly beautiful.
-I knew that was a thing.

14:39.962 --> 14:44.008
Really? I mean, it's pretty,
but isn't it a little much?

14:47.970 --> 14:49.972
I guess it's just not what I imagined.

14:51.974 --> 14:54.184
Well, honey, you can try another.

14:54.268 --> 14:58.063
I mean, there's still that ivory silk taffeta
and that one.

14:58.147 --> 15:00.524
You know,
the one with the fitted bodice.

15:02.526 --> 15:04.528
Oh, it's just amazing.

15:07.865 --> 15:09.658
Mick, we've known each other for years.

15:09.742 --> 15:12.870
You gotta help me out here.
You can't replace my crew.

15:12.953 --> 15:15.831
Paul, I verified the specs.
I walked and measured the sites.

15:15.915 --> 15:18.459
-I was at every pour.
-So you believe me?

15:18.542 --> 15:21.086
I did until I hired Bill Farrell
from Farrell Concrete.

15:21.170 --> 15:24.006
He said you were cutting corners
in ways he couldn't imagine.

15:24.089 --> 15:28.302
That's what made it work so well.
I poured fast so you could build slow.

15:28.385 --> 15:30.262
And we never missed a deadline.

15:30.346 --> 15:34.016
-Are you saying I'm complicit in this?
-No. What I'm saying is, we're partners.

15:34.099 --> 15:37.561
Yeah. And when we partnered up,
we talked about doing the right thing.

15:37.645 --> 15:40.898
Well, I'm sorry if I don't follow
your moral code,

15:40.981 --> 15:43.108
in building or partnerships.

15:43.192 --> 15:44.610
[♪♪♪]

15:44.693 --> 15:45.986
Are you threatening me, Paul?

15:46.070 --> 15:49.239
When the foundation crumbles,
the building does too.

15:49.323 --> 15:51.700
If I'm going down,
you're going down with me.

15:56.163 --> 15:57.247
He looked angry.

15:58.082 --> 15:59.333
Got a moment to talk?

15:59.416 --> 16:03.003
Yeah, depends on whether or not
you're gonna threaten me too.

16:03.087 --> 16:04.630
No, I think you're safe.

16:04.713 --> 16:07.675
-Actually, I came for some advice.
-Okay.

16:07.758 --> 16:09.593
I just had a meeting with Uncle Thomas.

16:09.677 --> 16:11.261
Well, less of a meeting

16:11.345 --> 16:14.765
and more of a lecture
on how I'm not a trial lawyer.

16:14.848 --> 16:18.310
Yeah, I heard about what you did.
You're lucky Thomas likes you so much.

16:18.394 --> 16:21.855
-I would've fired you on the spot.
-Ha. Yeah, you would.

16:21.939 --> 16:25.234
Look, I know what I did was wrong.
I made a mistake, I realize that.

16:25.317 --> 16:26.986
And I'm gonna make it right,

16:27.069 --> 16:30.155
but I'm looking at this case
and I know that I can win it.

16:30.990 --> 16:35.369
It's not about winning or losing.
Point is, it wasn't your choice to make.

16:35.452 --> 16:37.496
When you work for somebody,
you do what they ask,

16:37.579 --> 16:40.749
and if you don't,
you have to suffer the consequences.

16:40.833 --> 16:42.835
[♪♪♪]

16:43.794 --> 16:44.628
Thanks.

16:46.046 --> 16:48.132
DONOVAN:
I just don't want you to throw it all away.

16:48.215 --> 16:51.010
I didn't throw it away. I made a choice.

16:52.011 --> 16:53.637
Maybe a little late.

16:53.721 --> 16:56.015
But I wanted to come home.
There's a difference.

16:56.098 --> 17:00.769
There is, but, uh, blowing up the band
just when things were taking off,

17:00.853 --> 17:02.354
you can't come back from that.

17:03.272 --> 17:05.232
Two coffees, black, please.

17:06.858 --> 17:08.652
I didn't blow up the band.

17:08.736 --> 17:12.196
When the tour was over,
contract was done, I left.

17:12.281 --> 17:13.824
You can't leave, Trace.

17:15.784 --> 17:18.037
You know the legend of the crossroads?

17:18.119 --> 17:20.414
You're standing there,
and they hand you that guitar,

17:21.290 --> 17:23.291
you take it for life.

17:23.375 --> 17:26.962
Best thing you can hope for
is to strike a little balance.

17:27.046 --> 17:28.505
Like you did with your daughter?

17:31.925 --> 17:33.343
I'm still working on that.

17:34.219 --> 17:36.555
But I do know, you can't give it up.

17:36.638 --> 17:39.266
Look, some things in life
are just more important.

17:39.349 --> 17:40.851
I didn't realize that until I left.

17:42.144 --> 17:42.978
Well...

17:43.937 --> 17:46.565
considering what's at stake,
I sure hope you're right.

17:47.649 --> 17:48.484
Good luck.

17:49.985 --> 17:52.071
[♪♪♪]

17:56.992 --> 17:59.703
-Hey, Abby.
-Hi.

18:00.621 --> 18:03.874
-Sorry. It looks like you're busy and--
-No, it's okay.

18:03.957 --> 18:06.210
I just wanted to say hello.

18:06.293 --> 18:07.586
Just a work thing.

18:08.587 --> 18:10.506
Some things never change, right?

18:10.589 --> 18:12.132
Maybe that's not such a bad thing.

18:13.967 --> 18:17.805
Yeah. Actually,
I'm just concerned about this client.

18:17.888 --> 18:21.350
-The stakes are really high, so...
-That's when you're at your best.

18:23.727 --> 18:27.606
Maybe, but I just have
this difficult decision to make,

18:27.689 --> 18:29.900
and I can't afford to be wrong and...

18:30.943 --> 18:32.402
I get it.

18:32.486 --> 18:35.572
It seems like the right decisions
are always the hardest ones to make...

18:37.783 --> 18:39.243
but I know you'll make the right one.

18:42.079 --> 18:43.664
[♪♪♪]

18:43.747 --> 18:44.790
Thanks, Trace.

18:47.376 --> 18:48.752
Hey.

18:48.836 --> 18:52.172
Uh, Kevin and Sarah got engaged.

18:53.257 --> 18:54.091
Really?

18:55.717 --> 18:57.136
That's great. I'm happy for them.

19:11.024 --> 19:12.025
[LAPTOP WHOOSHES]

19:12.693 --> 19:14.987
BREE:
You did your book-reading in Italian?

19:15.070 --> 19:18.282
Yeah. Although the moderator was
a little flummoxed by my accent.

19:18.365 --> 19:20.117
You know, it was vaguely Sicilian.

19:21.076 --> 19:23.328
-The Godfather?
-Yeah.

19:23.412 --> 19:25.789
When I was growing up,
if I wasn't reading Dostoyevsky,

19:25.873 --> 19:28.125
I fancied myself
as Michael and Sonny's brother.

19:28.208 --> 19:29.251
-Oh, really?
-Mm-hm.

19:29.334 --> 19:32.045
Somehow, I don't really see you
as one of the Corleones.

19:32.129 --> 19:34.798
-That's exactly what my mother said.
-Smart.

19:34.882 --> 19:38.427
-She said I might be deeply disturbed.
-What did you say?

19:39.553 --> 19:42.973
[IN ITALIAN ACCENT]
"Revenge is a dish best served cold."

19:43.974 --> 19:44.808
Okay.

19:44.892 --> 19:47.728
[IN NORMAL VOICE]
Hey, why don't you do book readings?

19:48.729 --> 19:49.605
I've done them.

19:50.480 --> 19:55.194
I just feel like, um, it's strange
reading it to people after all the...

19:56.278 --> 19:57.946
pain it took to bring it to life.

19:58.030 --> 20:00.199
I kind of feel like
it's not a part of me anymore.

20:01.200 --> 20:02.326
-Hm.
SIMON: Mm.

20:04.703 --> 20:07.164
-What?
-Well, you just...

20:08.624 --> 20:10.125
You seem content.

20:10.209 --> 20:12.127
[♪♪♪]

20:12.211 --> 20:13.253
I guess I am.

20:13.712 --> 20:14.588
Mm.

20:17.382 --> 20:22.888
Oh. When I was in Rome,
I picked up a rare first edition,

20:22.971 --> 20:24.598
Alice di Le Avventure.

20:24.681 --> 20:27.809
-Alice in Wonderland, 1872.
-Wow.

20:27.893 --> 20:29.394
Still in perfect condition.

20:30.646 --> 20:32.314
I'll bring it next time I'm over.

20:35.817 --> 20:36.777
Sure.

20:42.574 --> 20:45.452
[COUNTRY MUSIC PLAYING
OVER SPEAKERS]

20:49.623 --> 20:51.875
Figured you'd be halfway
to Nashville by now.

20:51.959 --> 20:55.128
-Figured you'd be re-tiling the bathrooms.
-Funny.

20:57.422 --> 20:59.383
I'm not the one giving up, Trace.

21:01.760 --> 21:04.638
I've never seen a man happy
walking away from his dreams.

21:05.931 --> 21:09.393
Which is why we all go home
every now and then, take a little break.

21:10.394 --> 21:11.645
You can't quit.

21:12.729 --> 21:15.649
This is not about a break, okay?

21:15.732 --> 21:18.193
It's about starting the next chapter.

21:18.694 --> 21:20.320
You know, it's about priorities.

21:20.404 --> 21:23.699
Being an adult and realizing
what's really important in life.

21:25.284 --> 21:27.411
At some point, we all gotta grow up.

21:28.829 --> 21:32.499
But you know that already.
So why are you really here?

21:36.211 --> 21:37.421
I'm trying to save the tour.

21:39.339 --> 21:40.173
And that's it?

21:46.388 --> 21:49.433
Howdy! My name's Donovan Wylie.

21:49.516 --> 21:51.184
[AUDIENCE CHEERING]

21:55.355 --> 21:57.983
If y'all don't mind,
I'd like to sing a song,

21:58.066 --> 22:01.528
but I'm gonna need some help
from my tour mate, Trace Riley!

22:05.073 --> 22:06.408
Coming up here or what?

22:08.035 --> 22:10.203
Ha-ha. Yeah, that's right.

22:13.540 --> 22:15.542
[PLAYING COUNTRY MUSIC]

22:16.376 --> 22:20.255
-Hey. You know this isn't gonna work.
-Yeah, we'll see.

22:27.596 --> 22:31.808
♪ I know how it feels
To hit a home run ♪

22:34.311 --> 22:37.981
♪ Ride a perfect wave
And never lose control ♪

22:41.568 --> 22:46.740
♪ Holding that guitar
When it's your first one ♪

22:46.823 --> 22:51.078
♪ But I knew it
From the moment that we kissed ♪

22:51.161 --> 22:53.663
♪ Nothing ever felt like this ♪

22:53.747 --> 22:57.459
♪ I can ride the wind
Walk on water ♪

22:57.542 --> 23:00.921
♪ Leap tall buildings at a single bound ♪

23:01.004 --> 23:04.382
♪ Whatever comes, it don't matter ♪

23:04.466 --> 23:09.638
♪ 'Cause I can fly
Ten miles off the ground ♪

23:10.931 --> 23:13.266
♪ The way I feel right now ♪♪

23:15.185 --> 23:16.478
[ROCK MUSIC PLAYING
OVER SPEAKERS]

23:16.603 --> 23:20.440
You know, your mom is really
into this whole wedding thing.

23:20.524 --> 23:22.567
Yeah. She can get pretty intense.

23:24.236 --> 23:26.279
-You okay with it?
-Yeah.

23:26.363 --> 23:31.034
Yeah, I mean, who wouldn't be okay
with lace and tulle and taffeta?

23:34.037 --> 23:35.997
No, not really.

23:40.544 --> 23:41.378
You okay?

23:43.004 --> 23:44.965
You seem distracted.

23:46.591 --> 23:47.467
No, I'm not.

23:49.719 --> 23:51.638
Our first call this morning

23:51.721 --> 23:53.223
was my old coach from high school.

23:53.723 --> 23:56.101
-Your football coach?
-Yeah.

23:58.603 --> 24:01.398
You know,
I had a few really tough years,

24:01.481 --> 24:04.109
with everything
that was going on at home, and...

24:05.527 --> 24:08.280
I just started going to school early.

24:09.531 --> 24:12.742
And then one day,
I noticed that the gym door was open,

24:12.826 --> 24:16.705
the coach told me, "Come on in.
Come work out if you like."

24:16.788 --> 24:17.664
So that's what I did.

24:18.790 --> 24:19.916
Every morning.

24:22.669 --> 24:25.297
I never even realized
that he was opening up the door for me

24:25.380 --> 24:26.923
so that I would have a place to go.

24:27.007 --> 24:29.009
[♪♪♪]

24:30.969 --> 24:32.262
He was protecting me.

24:33.972 --> 24:35.974
And that's what you do for others now.

24:39.186 --> 24:42.731
I had no idea
that his wife had passed away.

24:44.858 --> 24:46.318
I should've been there for him.

24:54.284 --> 24:56.494
Are you still stressing over Simon?

24:56.578 --> 24:58.914
-All three of them.
-I thought there were only two.

24:58.997 --> 25:01.166
I thought so too,
but then I started thinking that

25:01.249 --> 25:03.376
on top of just Simon
and the actor playing Simon,

25:03.460 --> 25:05.754
I think there's a third,
an impostor Simon,

25:05.837 --> 25:08.381
who came to Chesapeake Shores
in lieu of my Simon.

25:08.465 --> 25:11.968
-So your date didn't go well.
-It went fine.

25:12.052 --> 25:14.262
It was like I was hanging out
with my best friend.

25:14.346 --> 25:16.932
We talked about literature and writing.

25:17.015 --> 25:19.267
-Your favorite things.
-Are they?

25:20.727 --> 25:23.521
-They are, yeah.
-It's what you two always talk about.

25:23.605 --> 25:27.651
I think I'm having an existential crisis,
Abby, or a literary one, I can't tell.

25:27.734 --> 25:31.738
-Maybe you should talk to him.
-Trust me, talking is not the problem.

25:31.821 --> 25:34.199
All we ever do is talk and talk and talk.

25:34.282 --> 25:38.078
Now I have to go to a rehearsal
to listen to more talking.

25:38.745 --> 25:39.829
Okay.

25:40.997 --> 25:42.123
Have fun.

25:44.668 --> 25:48.755
Del, I left word again
to get those documents from Porter,

25:48.838 --> 25:50.465
and I've sent them three e-mails...

25:50.548 --> 25:53.468
Abby, you can stop working now.

25:54.552 --> 25:57.847
Porter Industries signed
with Hunter Drew &amp; Associates,

25:57.931 --> 25:59.516
and these files are going back.

26:00.558 --> 26:03.353
-Why, what's wrong?
-I think your e-mail scared them.

26:04.020 --> 26:06.022
[♪♪♪]

26:07.190 --> 26:11.361
Del, if this fund collapses,
it's gonna hurt a lot of people

26:11.444 --> 26:14.072
who've trusted them
with their life savings.

26:14.155 --> 26:17.033
Abby, this isn't from me.
It's from New York.

26:17.117 --> 26:20.036
They are no longer
a prospective client of ours.

26:21.288 --> 26:22.914
Now you have to walk away.

26:26.918 --> 26:29.504
I already said goodbye once,
I don't wanna say it again.

26:29.587 --> 26:31.172
I don't think the inn's gonna mind.

26:31.256 --> 26:34.634
-I just don't want it to end.
-I know. Me either.

26:35.635 --> 26:39.681
If it wasn't for you and the inn,
I'd still be waiting tables at Sally's.

26:39.764 --> 26:42.892
Or running a multimillion-dollar
corporation for my parents.

26:42.976 --> 26:44.561
One or the other.

26:44.644 --> 26:47.397
-We had so many amazing memories.
-We did.

26:47.480 --> 26:51.735
-Scones, quiches, our first kiss.
-Under the sprinklers.

26:51.818 --> 26:53.320
Christmas on the deck.

26:54.779 --> 26:56.406
I would go anywhere to be with you.

26:56.489 --> 26:57.907
[♪♪♪]

26:57.991 --> 26:59.993
Where will we go?
What are we gonna do?

27:00.076 --> 27:02.037
-Jess...
-I don't even know where to begin.

27:02.120 --> 27:03.496
Close your eyes.

27:04.080 --> 27:08.668
David, you can't just close your eyes
and wish for things to be different.

27:08.752 --> 27:10.128
Close them.

27:13.340 --> 27:14.841
What?

27:14.924 --> 27:15.925
Okay, open them.

27:18.678 --> 27:23.224
Look, we found perfect once.
We can find it again.

27:25.018 --> 27:26.936
A new B and B won't be the same.

27:28.229 --> 27:30.774
Yeah, but maybe it'll be better.

27:33.360 --> 27:34.569
Maybe.

27:51.211 --> 27:55.006
Um, first off, I'd like to explain
what happened the other day.

27:55.673 --> 27:58.426
Given our long-standing relationship,

27:58.510 --> 28:02.597
over time, some mistakes
can be expected--

28:02.680 --> 28:04.974
And these issues need to be discussed,

28:05.058 --> 28:08.144
specifically the idea
of taking this to court.

28:09.854 --> 28:10.772
We agree.

28:12.023 --> 28:16.361
You agree we should not go to court?

28:18.238 --> 28:22.283
Yes. After a long discussion
with our client,

28:22.367 --> 28:25.787
we believe that we will file
for immediate settlement.

28:25.870 --> 28:29.833
So sign, and we can put this to bed.

28:30.834 --> 28:33.420
-If you think we're just going to sign off--
-We'll sign.

28:34.796 --> 28:35.630
What?

28:36.548 --> 28:38.258
They're not building the refinery.

28:39.175 --> 28:40.176
We won.

28:40.260 --> 28:42.262
[♪♪♪]

28:45.140 --> 28:48.727
Luckily for you,
today I'm having a sale on verbs.

28:50.603 --> 28:55.108
Well, I was hoping
this time it wouldn't be just...

28:55.191 --> 28:59.154
I feel like this moment
really sets up the ending.

28:59.237 --> 29:02.115
And I love
how Jace's passionate presence

29:02.198 --> 29:04.909
really pulls Melanie out
of her metaphorical attic.

29:04.993 --> 29:06.077
BREE:
Mmm.

29:06.161 --> 29:08.580
Yeah. I love it too.

29:10.749 --> 29:14.252
Is Jace based on your boyfriend?
The one that was here?

29:15.128 --> 29:16.588
Uh...

29:16.671 --> 29:19.966
I mean, yeah, more or less.

29:20.049 --> 29:21.384
[HANNAH CHUCKLES]

29:21.468 --> 29:23.094
And that makes you Melanie.

29:25.054 --> 29:27.223
Loosely inspired by, I guess.

29:28.475 --> 29:32.520
Well, if I was dating someone
with that much passion and charisma,

29:32.604 --> 29:34.355
I'd be writing about my love life too.

29:37.317 --> 29:38.151
Yeah.

29:38.276 --> 29:39.736
[♪♪♪]

29:40.278 --> 29:44.157
Simon is very passionate.

29:45.825 --> 29:49.287
Yup. Definitely Simon.

29:56.836 --> 29:58.671
-Nice work.
-Thank you.

30:03.593 --> 30:06.387
You see? Nothing to worry about.

30:06.471 --> 30:08.056
I'm reassigning you.

30:08.139 --> 30:09.516
What? Why?

30:09.599 --> 30:11.643
Connor, an attorney never asks
a question

30:11.726 --> 30:13.645
he doesn't already know the answer to.

30:13.728 --> 30:15.855
Or take unnecessary risks.

30:15.939 --> 30:17.899
That's why we're successful
at what we do.

30:17.982 --> 30:21.236
I understand, but in this case,
taking a risk, it made them blink.

30:21.319 --> 30:24.239
-And if they didn't and we lost?
-But we didn't.

30:25.782 --> 30:30.662
Connor, whether you won or--
Got lucky or not,

30:30.745 --> 30:32.914
I need to know
you're not going to go rogue.

30:33.832 --> 30:36.167
I'm putting you on research.

30:36.251 --> 30:38.461
Research? I started on research.

30:40.171 --> 30:44.509
Connor, you're smart, aggressive,
all the makings of a great attorney.

30:44.592 --> 30:50.056
If you can't separate what you want
from what your client needs,

30:50.139 --> 30:52.183
your worst enemy is gonna be you.

30:55.812 --> 30:57.814
[♪♪♪]

31:04.320 --> 31:05.947
So Simon's not Simon?

31:06.030 --> 31:09.033
No, Simon is Simon,
but the character Simon isn't Simon.

31:09.117 --> 31:10.159
That's a problem, why?

31:10.243 --> 31:14.873
Because I'm realizing that my ideal Simon
is kind of like Simon meets Martin.

31:14.956 --> 31:17.709
"Mimon." Or "Siton."
Haven't figured out which yet.

31:17.792 --> 31:18.710
I don't like this.

31:18.793 --> 31:21.754
Hey, remember, open house, open mind.

31:21.838 --> 31:24.090
We promised we'd see 10 houses
before we decide.

31:24.173 --> 31:28.303
Martin and I had passion.
Whereas Simon and I have conversations.

31:28.386 --> 31:30.763
Maybe you can talk your way into a kiss.

31:30.847 --> 31:33.808
Or maybe we just talked our way
into the friend zone.

31:33.892 --> 31:35.643
The friend zone is a one-way ticket.

31:35.727 --> 31:38.354
You just gotta charm your way in,
then ask for what you want.

31:38.438 --> 31:40.064
What if he doesn't respond?

31:40.148 --> 31:44.110
You are smart, successful, beautiful.
Any guy would be crazy not to want you.

31:44.611 --> 31:45.862
JESS:
Except for David.

31:49.490 --> 31:50.700
Why am I here, again?

31:50.783 --> 31:52.035
For moral support.

31:52.118 --> 31:55.038
-For Jess? She has David.
-No, for me.

31:55.121 --> 31:59.208
I am about to blow the whistle
on the Porter Fund,

31:59.292 --> 32:02.211
and I'm scared out of my mind.

32:04.923 --> 32:08.051
You got this, Abby Brockovich.

32:10.970 --> 32:13.056
[♪♪♪]

32:38.373 --> 32:41.542
[SOFTLY]
It's perfect.

32:48.508 --> 32:50.176
I come bearing gifts.

32:51.761 --> 32:55.390
Pinot noir? We're not wine-tasting
for the wedding, are we?

32:55.473 --> 32:58.559
Nope. This is about me.

33:01.312 --> 33:06.859
I didn't plan graduation parties,
or Abby's wedding.

33:08.903 --> 33:10.655
I know I can't make up
for what happened,

33:10.738 --> 33:12.490
but I don't wanna make
that mistake again.

33:19.330 --> 33:21.958
I came back here, home...

33:23.501 --> 33:26.587
to try and repair the cracks that I made.

33:26.671 --> 33:27.547
We made.

33:29.007 --> 33:32.593
Lately I've been feeling that
since our kids seem to be okay,

33:32.677 --> 33:36.723
maybe there's just not a lot left
for me to do.

33:37.807 --> 33:39.642
The wedding dress and the planning?

33:40.184 --> 33:41.060
Hmph.

33:43.104 --> 33:45.857
Don't worry about not being part
of this family, Megan.

33:47.025 --> 33:49.485
[♪♪♪]

33:51.779 --> 33:53.740
What now? What do I do?

33:54.949 --> 33:58.619
Whatever you want.
I mean, it's kind of wonderful, isn't it?

34:06.127 --> 34:07.962
So, what do you want, Mick?

34:10.047 --> 34:11.090
I don't know.

34:14.761 --> 34:16.304
That doesn't sound like you.

34:18.806 --> 34:20.391
Dilpher's been indicted.

34:21.601 --> 34:24.228
And he's named me a coconspirator
in his fraud case.

34:24.312 --> 34:26.606
Says I authorized...

34:26.688 --> 34:30.025
substandard foundations
in close to 200 buildings.

34:32.570 --> 34:34.906
-But that's not true.
-No, it's not.

34:36.324 --> 34:37.909
But it might not matter.

34:44.748 --> 34:46.375
I stopped by the hospital.

34:46.458 --> 34:48.878
The nurse said
Coach had already checked out.

34:48.960 --> 34:49.837
That's good.

34:50.922 --> 34:53.507
He didn't have a single visitor.

34:53.591 --> 34:57.136
Coach was a pretty private guy.
Bet no one knew. I didn't.

34:58.346 --> 34:59.639
I just wanted to say thank you.

35:00.473 --> 35:03.434
I think saving his life
was saying thank you.

35:04.018 --> 35:06.896
Yeah, maybe. It's just not the same.

35:11.025 --> 35:14.487
When I was studying for the bar,
I was crazy stressed,

35:14.570 --> 35:16.447
and I bumped into him
at the supermarket.

35:16.531 --> 35:18.157
We talked for a little bit,

35:18.241 --> 35:21.119
he invited me to the high school
to play some catch.

35:22.203 --> 35:24.122
We tossed the ball around for an hour.

35:24.205 --> 35:27.041
Said he was doing it
to loosen up his arm.

35:28.084 --> 35:30.419
But I knew he was doing it for me. Yeah.

35:30.503 --> 35:31.921
[♪♪♪]

35:32.004 --> 35:33.589
He never stopped coaching.

35:47.520 --> 35:49.230
Knocking out the club sound system

35:49.313 --> 35:52.024
so you and Donovan could play
a three-hour acoustic set.

35:52.108 --> 35:53.109
Bold move.

35:55.069 --> 35:59.407
You know, I've spent the last seven years
serving in small-town clubs.

35:59.490 --> 36:03.202
What you and Donovan did last night,
doesn't belong here.

36:05.371 --> 36:08.332
Trace, you've played some big venues.

36:08.416 --> 36:10.001
Doesn't matter.

36:10.084 --> 36:15.548
All those crowds, all that money,
couldn't fill the hole in my gut.

36:16.966 --> 36:18.259
[♪♪♪]

36:18.384 --> 36:22.263
So you gave it all up to come back
and be a glorified handyman.

36:24.515 --> 36:26.017
Something like that.

36:35.526 --> 36:39.071
You helped me a lot,
and I'm gonna miss you.

36:40.239 --> 36:44.368
But just know that I'll always be with you,
and you with me.

36:46.704 --> 36:47.872
DAVID:
Saying goodbye?

36:50.124 --> 36:53.377
I just don't want her to think
that I'm abandoning her,

36:53.461 --> 36:55.880
think that I'm gonna forget her.

36:57.048 --> 36:59.175
-What's that?
-Open it.

37:01.093 --> 37:02.428
[♪♪♪]

37:03.471 --> 37:05.681
-A sprinkler.
-Yeah.

37:05.765 --> 37:09.101
So we'll always have a little bit
of the inn with us, no matter where we go.

37:10.102 --> 37:12.688
I love you. I love us.

37:12.772 --> 37:15.191
Yeah, we're pretty good, aren't we?

37:15.274 --> 37:16.776
It's gonna be okay.

37:20.029 --> 37:21.322
[♪♪♪]

37:21.405 --> 37:23.658
MICK: Next time you're here,
we should go sailing.

37:23.741 --> 37:26.994
Absolutely.
This time around was all business.

37:27.078 --> 37:30.831
Yeah, I heard. Connor told me.
You're a far kinder man than I.

37:30.915 --> 37:32.625
Well, that goes without saying.

37:32.708 --> 37:34.794
Yeah, I know, but I said it anyway.

37:34.877 --> 37:38.714
Connor's a good kid. He just has
a little too much of you in him.

37:38.798 --> 37:40.424
Yeah, unfortunately.

37:41.425 --> 37:43.219
So, what's the latest on Dilpher?

37:44.220 --> 37:46.472
They're shutting down construction
on all my projects

37:46.555 --> 37:49.141
until an investigation can be done.

37:49.225 --> 37:50.351
Can you float it?

37:50.434 --> 37:54.855
I got reserves, I can keep my subs paid.
We'll be fine.

37:54.939 --> 37:57.108
As a lawyer, what are we looking at?

37:57.191 --> 38:00.778
As a lawyer, I'd say you have
a better-than-fighting chance

38:00.861 --> 38:03.364
to prove you were never engaged
in fraud.

38:04.991 --> 38:06.200
And as my brother?

38:07.201 --> 38:12.415
Even if you clear your name legally,
uh, your reputation might take a hit.

38:12.498 --> 38:14.041
I know that hurts you worse.

38:16.669 --> 38:18.671
[♪♪♪]

38:22.216 --> 38:24.176
COACH:
Why do we have to go outside?

38:24.260 --> 38:27.596
Because I need the fresh air.
And I could use some exercise.

38:27.680 --> 38:28.931
Hey, Kev.

38:30.725 --> 38:32.810
[CHANTING]
Coach! Coach! Coach!

38:32.893 --> 38:34.645
Coach! Coach! Coach!

38:34.729 --> 38:36.856
Coach! Coach! Coach!

38:36.939 --> 38:38.441
Coach! Coach! Coach!

38:38.524 --> 38:40.234
You don't have to do this.

38:40.318 --> 38:42.611
-Yeah, I did.
-Coach! Coach! Coach!

38:42.695 --> 38:44.071
[ALL CHEERING]

38:45.323 --> 38:46.991
TRACE:
Whoo! Yeah!

38:48.659 --> 38:50.661
[PLAYING COUNTRY MUSIC]

38:54.623 --> 38:56.417
Thanks for fixing the sound system.

38:56.500 --> 39:00.087
Hearing every note
just makes this band even worse.

39:00.171 --> 39:02.381
I should have thought that one through.

39:02.465 --> 39:04.550
Oh, Donovan left something
behind the bar.

39:26.655 --> 39:29.241
"To the man who grabbed the guitar
and walked away."

39:31.410 --> 39:32.495
[CHUCKLES]

39:36.749 --> 39:40.669
These are the latest books.
All orders and accounts are up to date.

39:40.753 --> 39:45.925
-Uh, okay. That's good.
-It's been a pleasure working with you.

39:47.051 --> 39:48.052
You're leaving?

39:48.135 --> 39:51.138
Got an offer to manage a chain
of waffle houses in the Mid-Atlantic.

39:52.390 --> 39:53.599
Does Mick know?

39:53.682 --> 39:57.144
It was his idea. He gave me my notice
as soon as he heard you were back.

39:58.312 --> 40:00.022
And if you ever go on tour again,

40:00.106 --> 40:02.441
we'd love to have you perform
at our establishments.

40:02.525 --> 40:05.277
Yeah, that's not gonna happen,
but thanks for the offer.

40:12.159 --> 40:14.787
Hey, Trace, will you do me a favor
and fire the band?

40:15.955 --> 40:17.289
-With pleasure.
-Cool.

40:17.373 --> 40:18.374
[TRACE CHUCKLES]

40:27.174 --> 40:30.970
Thank you for doing this. I just wanna
make sure that all the beats are there.

40:31.053 --> 40:35.141
My pleasure. Though I do warn you,
I'm not really much of an actor.

40:35.224 --> 40:38.018
Oh. I think you'll be able to jump right in.

40:38.102 --> 40:41.605
Oh, okay. I guess, away we go.

40:43.107 --> 40:43.941
Melanie.

40:44.108 --> 40:45.025
[♪♪♪]

40:45.526 --> 40:49.155
-Oh...
-Heh-heh. Jace. You're back.

40:50.114 --> 40:52.992
You know how hard it is for me
to stay away.

40:53.075 --> 40:56.287
You never could pass up
a decent literary trope.

40:56.370 --> 41:00.374
Or a strong female protagonist.
I think I've actually said that one.

41:00.458 --> 41:03.794
Um, conveniently,
I've been working on some new pages,

41:03.878 --> 41:06.172
and I'd love to know what you think.

41:06.255 --> 41:08.132
The curse of being a wordsmith.

41:08.591 --> 41:12.178
Luckily for you,
today I have a sale on verbs.

41:12.261 --> 41:14.054
I've definitely said that.

41:15.222 --> 41:16.432
Um...

41:16.515 --> 41:17.933
Well... Ahem.

41:19.477 --> 41:23.230
I was hoping that this time
it wouldn't be just words.

41:23.314 --> 41:24.398
Brilliant.

41:25.941 --> 41:27.193
What do you have in mind?

41:28.861 --> 41:33.115
Oh, I could think of one or two things.

41:33.199 --> 41:34.283
Really?

41:36.785 --> 41:39.163
I can only think of one.

41:52.092 --> 41:53.302
How was that?

41:54.720 --> 41:56.722
[♪♪♪]

41:57.556 --> 41:58.641
That was nice.

42:12.488 --> 42:13.489
[CLEARS THROAT]

42:14.031 --> 42:17.618
Del. What's, um, going on?

42:19.161 --> 42:23.082
Somebody leaked the Porter financials
to the Tribune.

42:26.418 --> 42:27.795
I couldn't let them hurt people.

42:28.921 --> 42:31.215
I'm sorry. I have no choice.

42:33.801 --> 42:38.264
You're officially suspended without pay,
pending a formal investigation.

42:38.722 --> 42:41.934
Please pack up your office
and turn in your keys.

42:42.476 --> 42:43.727
[♪♪♪]

42:44.937 --> 42:46.230
I'm so sorry.

42:47.231 --> 42:48.232
So am I.

42:51.610 --> 42:53.028
But I'm glad you did it.

43:07.001 --> 43:09.003
[♪♪♪]

44:01.180 --> 44:02.973
NARRATOR:
Next week on Chesapeake Shores:

44:03.057 --> 44:05.893
-You always did have good taste in dance partners.
TRACE: She's not ready.

44:06.060 --> 44:07.686
Don't you think you ought to
leave that up to her?

44:07.853 --> 44:09.897
-It's what everyone wants.
-What do you want?

44:10.022 --> 44:11.774
-I just want you.
-You've been served.

44:11.940 --> 44:14.568
We found the perfect inn
that someone else wants to buy.

44:14.652 --> 44:17.112
I feel like we're not connecting
and I don't know why.

44:17.321 --> 44:21.033
I don't want to walk away from what could be
by fearing what was.

